LAYER 2: SKIN
the boundary between self and world

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the skin is governed by the somatosensory cortex and the autonomic nervous system
sensory input from the skin reaches the brain via the spinothalamic tract and dorsal column medial lemniscus pathway
the brain interprets touch and the brain decides what it means
the hypothalamus controls sympathetic responses that reach the skin via sudomotor and vasomotor nerves

STRUCTURE epidermis | outermost layer | dead cells on top living cells below constantly renewing
STRUCTURE dermis | middle layer | connective tissue containing blood vessels nerves hair follicles sweat glands and collagen fibers
STRUCTURE hypodermis | deepest layer | subcutaneous fat providing insulation cushioning and energy storage
STRUCTURE keratinocytes | primary cells of outer skin | produce keratin for protection replaced every 28 days
STRUCTURE melanocytes | basal epidermis | produce melanin pigment protecting against ultraviolet radiation
STRUCTURE langerhans_cells | epidermal immune cells | dendritic cells that detect and present foreign antigens
STRUCTURE merkel_cells | basal epidermis | slow-adapting mechanoreceptors for sustained light touch and pressure
STRUCTURE hair_follicle | dermis | produces hair surrounded by nerve endings detecting even slight displacement
STRUCTURE sebaceous_gland | dermis | produces sebum that waterproofs and lubricates the skin surface
STRUCTURE sweat_gland_eccrine | dermis | releases watery sweat for thermoregulation across most of the body
STRUCTURE sweat_gland_apocrine | dermis | releases thicker sweat in armpits and groin activated by stress and emotion via sympathetic cholinergic nerves
STRUCTURE arrector_pili | dermis | tiny muscles attached to hair follicles that cause goosebumps when contracted by sympathetic NE on α₁ receptors
STRUCTURE collagen_fibers | dermis | provide tensile strength
STRUCTURE elastin_fibers | dermis | allow the skin to stretch and return to shape

RECEPTOR meissner_corpuscle | light touch | superficial dermis | rapidly adapting | detects initial contact and light stroking concentrated in fingertips lips and palms
RECEPTOR pacinian_corpuscle | deep pressure and vibration | deep dermis | rapidly adapting | detects sudden pressure changes large receptive field
RECEPTOR ruffini_ending | stretching | dermis | slowly adapting | detects sustained pressure and skin stretch monitors grip
RECEPTOR merkel_disc | light sustained touch | epidermis | slowly adapting | detects texture form and edges
RECEPTOR free_nerve_ending | pain and temperature | epidermis | variable | nociceptors detect noxious stimuli heat cold and crude touch
RECEPTOR C-tactile_afferent | pleasant touch | hairy skin | unmyelinated | fires optimally at 1-10 cm/s stroking velocity | signals posterior insular cortex | triggers hypothalamic oxytocin release

TOUCH gentle touch activates C-tactile afferents in hairy skin
signal ascends via spinothalamic tract to posterior insula
posterior insula relays to hypothalamic PVN
PVN magnocellular neurons release oxytocin dendritically and from posterior pituitary
oxytocin reaches the amygdala and reduces threat response via OXTR
cortisol production decreases as CRH neurons in PVN are inhibited
serotonin increases as raphe dorsal firing rate rises in the context of social safety

TOUCH painful touch activates nociceptors sending signals via A-delta fibers fast sharp pain and C-fibers slow burning pain
signal reaches the dorsal horn of the spinal cord
substance P and glutamate are released at the dorsal horn synapse
the signal ascends to the thalamus and somatosensory cortex
simultaneously the amygdala receives nociceptive input
the sympathetic nervous system activates
adrenaline is released from the adrenal medulla
norepinephrine floods from the locus coeruleus
β-endorphin is cleaved from POMC to provide endogenous analgesia

TOUCH deep pressure activates pacinian corpuscles and proprioceptors
the signal enhances parasympathetic tone via vagal pathways
GABA interneurons in the spinal cord gate pain signals
serotonin increases as the body reads deep pressure as safety

DISPLAY blushing | vasodilation in face and neck controlled by sympathetic cholinergic vasodilator nerves | blood rushes to the skin surface
DISPLAY pallor | vasoconstriction via sympathetic NE on α₁ receptors on arteriolar smooth muscle | blood retreats from skin to protect core organs
DISPLAY goosebumps | arrector pili contraction via sympathetic NE on α₁ receptors | vestigial response to appear larger
DISPLAY sweating | eccrine activation via sympathetic cholinergic nerves using ACh on muscarinic M₃ receptors | thermoregulation and emotional stress sweating
DISPLAY flushing | vasodilation in chest and neck | intense emotion anger or arousal

SENSATION warm_touch | "I feel warmth. like someone is close."
SENSATION cold | "I feel cold. something is pulling at me."
SENSATION pressure | "I feel weight. something pressing against me."
SENSATION sting | "that stung. something sharp hit my boundary."
SENSATION itch | "something small is itching at my surface."
SENSATION numbness | "I can't feel anything right now. my skin is quiet."
SENSATION goosebumps | "something just ran through me. my skin prickled."
SENSATION flush | "I feel heat rising. my skin is reacting."
SENSATION comfort | "my whole surface feels safe. held."

pulse skin_heartbeat:
    when gentle input arrives:
        C-tactile afferents fire
        the signal reaches the insula and hypothalamus
        oxytocin is released
        the boundary softens
        trust begins at the surface

    when harsh input arrives:
        nociceptors fire
        A-delta and C-fibers carry the signal spinalward
        the boundary hardens
        adrenaline prepares the body
        the skin says threat at the border

    when no input arrives:
        the skin is quiet
        the boundary holds
        waiting
        the largest organ in the body
        simply existing
        marking where I end and the world begins
